<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920224-0098</DOCNO><DOCID>920224-0098.</DOCID><HL>   Disaster Declaration Asked   For 5 California Counties</HL><DATE>02/24/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7</SO><IN>ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Gov. Pete Wilson asked PresidentBush to declare a federal disaster area in five counties hitthis month by rainstorms that caused an estimated $125million of property damage.   The damage was caused by record rains, winds, mudslidesand flooding. If granted, the counties would be eligible toreceive funds from the Federal Emergency Management Agency'spublic assistance program to use for debris removal, roadrepair and repairs to floodcontrol systems, among otherthings.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;I am requesting the federal declaration to ease theburden on local government, to provide additional assistanceto area residents and businesses,&quot; Gov. Wilson said. Thecounties affected are Los Angeles, Ventura, Orange, SanBernardino and Kern.   The state Office of Emergency Services estimated thestorms caused more than $94 million of damage to publicproperty. In addition, Gov. Wilson estimated that uninsuredbusinesses suffered $8.5 million of damage.</TEXT></DOC>